R: @jeffposnick @addyosmani @gauntface

This PR updates our DBWrapper implementation to use a WIP general-purpose IDB wrapper library I'm developing. Note that in this PR I've just updated the code to the new API; I haven't taken advantage of any of the new features. We can do that in another PR.

Notable changes:

1) I've removed the `indexedDBHelper` export and now just export a `DBWrapper` class, which packages can consume directly.

2) The `DBWrapper` class handles opening the connection behind the scenes (prior to making any transactions), so our code doesn't have to worry about it. This allows us to create instances in constructor functions since it happens sync.

```js
// No connection is made by doing this.
const db = new DBWrapper('my-db', 1);

// This calls `await db.open()` in the background
const entries = await db.getAll('my-store');
```

3) `DBWrapper` has a general purpose query function called `getAllMatching()`, which is similar to `getAll()` but it supports specifying an [index](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/IDBIndex), [direction](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/IDBCursor/direction), [key range](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/IDBKeyRange), and count (like "limit" in SQL) as well as optionally returning the keys (useful for `autoIncrement:true`).

There are places in our code where we call `getAll()` and then filter the results. This is inefficient since in many cases we can do the filter via the `getAllMatching()`. For example, `workbox-cache-expiration` can request only entries with timestamps greater than X by doing something like this:

```js
const expiredEntries = await db.getAllMatching('store-name', {
  index: 'timestamp',
  query: IDBKeyRange.lowerBound(X),
});
```

Or if you wanted to get just the entry with the newest timestamp, you can do something like this:

```js
const [oldestEntry] = await db.getAllMatching('store-name', {
  index: 'timestamp',
  direction: 'prev',
  count: 1,
});
```

Both of these are much more efficient than doing `getAll()` since they only search/return a subset of the object store.

R: @jeffposnick @addyosmani @gauntface

To address #940, this PR updates `workbox-sw` to instantiate and only expose a singleton instance of `WorkboxSW` on `self.workbox`. To handle custom options, it adds a new `.setConfig()` method.

Here's an example of what the usage would look like with these changes:

```js
importScripts('path/to/workbox-sw.prod.js');

workbox.setConfig({
  // ...
});

// Now it's safe to run the following code since `workbox` knows to
// dynamcially load all dependencies.
workbox.googleAnalytics.initialize();
```

* * *

Breaking changes:

* This no longer supports the idea of a *default* export handling the majority use cases on the namespace -- instead it's exposed on `workbox.packageName.default`.
* This also removes the `disableModuleImports` option, as I don't really see a use case for `workbox-sw` without the loader features.

- Adds an internal logging API to core.
    - Default log level is verbose on dev.
    - Default log level is warn on prod.
- Updated to latest rollup version to fix a bug in the rollup-stream version.
- gulp.watch is added for any manual testing you want to do in the browser (see test/workbox-core/static/logger.html)
- This PR also changes the build so that dev builds are no longer minified.

API Example for external developers using browser bundles:
```javascript
workbox.core.default.logLevel = workbox.core.LOG_LEVELS.error;
```
API Example for external developers using ES2015 modules:
```javascript
import core from 'workbox-core';
import {LOG_LEVELS} from 'workbox-core';

core.logLevel = LOG_LEVELS.error;
```

For internal workbox-libraries (which will do the logging):

```javascript
import {_private} from  'workbox-core';
_private.logger.log('Example');
_private.logger.debug('Example');
_private.logger.warn('Example');
_private.logger.error('Example');

_private.logger.groupCollapsed('Group title');
_private.logger.groupEnd();
```

